To create a schematic illustration of the impact of an accreted clump on the stellar surface using TikZ in LaTeX, we can model it as an idealized mechanical system comprising two springs connected to two masses. Here's a step-by-step guide to generating the TikZ code:

1. **Define the masses and springs**: We will use nodes for the masses and lines with different spring constants for the springs.
2. **Positioning the masses and springs**: We will position the masses along a horizontal line and place the springs between them.
3. **Labeling the components**: We will label the masses and springs with their respective symbols.

Here is the TikZ code to achieve this:

```latex
\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.5]
    % Define styles for nodes and edges
    \tikzset{
        mass/.style={circle, draw, fill=blue!20, minimum size=1cm},
        spring/.style={thick, ->, >=stealth}
    }

    % Position the masses
    \node[mass] (M) at (0,0) {M};
    \node[mass] (m) at (4,0) {$m \ll M$};

    % Draw the springs
    \draw[spring, bend left=45] (M.east) to node[midway, above] {$K$} (m.west);
    \draw[spring, bend right=45] (M.west) to node[midway, below] {$k$} (m.east);

    % Add labels
    \node[above=2pt] at (M.north) {Mass $M$};
    \node[above=2pt] at (m.north) {Mass $m \ll M$};
    \node[left=2pt] at (M.west) {Spring $K$};
    \node[right=2pt] at (m.east) {Spring $k$};
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```

